  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What belt types are used in packaging?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Six primary types: PVC (general-purpose, lowest cost), polyurethane (FDA food-grade), silicone (high-temperature bakery), rubber (heavy-duty incline), modular plastic (repairable, food-grade), and metal mesh (ovens, freezers). Selection depends on product, temperature, FDA requirements, and budget.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What belt material is FDA-approved for food?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Polyurethane, silicone, acetal and polypropylene modular plastics, and stainless steel are available in FDA 21 CFR 177-compliant formulations. Polyurethane is the most widely specified because it combines FDA compliance, abrasion resistance, and easy cleaning. Blue and white colors aid visual <a href="/conveyor-functions/inspection-detection/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">contamination detection</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How long does a conveyor belt last?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>PVC: 1-3 years. PU: 2-5 years. Modular plastic: 5-10+ years (modules individually replaceable). Metal mesh: 3-7 years. Proper tracking, tensioning, and cleaning extend belt life. Improper tracking can destroy a new belt in weeks. See the <a href="/resources/conveyor-maintenance/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">maintenance guide</a> for procedures.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a modular conveyor belt?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Interlocking plastic modules connected by hinge rods. Damaged modules pop out and replacements snap in , no belt removal needed. Sprocket-driven (no tracking issues). Available in FDA-compliant materials. Higher upfront cost than flat belts but 5-10+ year life and lower maintenance cost. Intralox, Rexnord, and Habasit are the primary manufacturers.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
